<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900604-0111</DOCNO><DOCID>900604-0111.</DOCID><HL>   U.S. Lawsuit Is Filed   In Shearson Account's   Securing SBA Loans</HL><DATE>06/04/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A7A</SO><CO>   SLH AXP</CO><IN>SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)DIVERSIFIED FINANCIAL SERVICES, FANNIE MAE, FREDDIE MAC (FIS)</IN><GV>FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)</GV><LP>   NEWARK, N.J. -- The federal government filed suit in U.S.District Court here, charging that a predecessor of the NewYork-based securities firm Shearson Lehman Hutton HoldingsInc. improperly disbursed the proceeds of an account.   The government claims that the account was put up assecurity for two loans, totaling $602,000, that the SmallBusiness Administration made to Connecticut Aerosols Inc.,Milford, Conn. Terms of the loans, which were made to thecompany in 1975 and 1978, required that at least $275,882 beleft in the account until the loans were paid, the complaintstates.</LP><TEXT>   Connecticut Aerosols and its president, John J. Franchini,defaulted on the loans, the civil action alleges. The SBAsought the account's proceeds, the complaint charges, butShearson or its predecessor, E.F. Hutton andamp; Co., &quot;liquidatedthe account and paid&quot; the proceeds to Mr. Franchini &quot;orotherwise disbursed&quot; them.   Shearson has refused to make any payment to thegovernment, the complaint states. The suit demands thatShearson pay the remaining principal and accrued interest onthe loans as of Feb. 1 -- a total $405,006 -- plus theinterest accrued since then.   A spokesman for Shearson said the firm, a subsidiary ofAmerican Express Co., New York, hadn't seen the complaint andcouldn't comment. Mr. Franchini couldn't be reached forcomment.</TEXT></DOC>